(1) Washington Street, at the S.E. corner of High Street. The elevated station at the right, is on High Street. The building in the background, is the entrance to the Brooklyn Bridge. The frame building in the corner, was once owned by a Rhode Island Senator named Peabody Wetmore. All the frame houses in the view, were demolished in September 1925.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, from a different angle.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

149 Washington Street, east side, between High (foreground) and Sands Streets, showing the Washington Hotel for men. This view also shows the High and Sands Streets stations of the Lexington and Myrtle Ave. Lines (B.M.T.).

May 24, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

155-157 Washington Street, at the N.E. corner of High Street, showing the High Street station of the Myrtle (B.M.T.) Ave. Elevated Line. The Heights moving picture theatre stood on the site of the drug store (no. 155) in 1929.

May 24, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
